    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Proponents of segregation often constructed a pseudo-scientific economic theory centered on the concept of \"white flight\" and the inevitable decline of property values in integrated neighborhoods. They argued that because white citizens would voluntarily sell their homes to non-white buyers due to social pressure and fear, this forced exit would create a ripple effect of mass selling, thereby driving down prices for all white owners in a specific area. Consequently, they framed segregation not as a choice, but as a necessary market correction mechanism to prevent this \"speculative decline\" and protect the wealth of the white middle class. By artificially restricting housing markets to maintain racial homogeneity, they claimed they were stabilizing the urban economy and ensuring that real estate investments remained safe and liquid for white buyers. This logic posited that true economic stability in cities required strict racial boundaries to prevent the perceived negative spill-over effects on property assessments and neighborhood tax bases.",
